uckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Badlington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Waddington   or   Watlington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Waddington","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name mostly from Waddington in Yorkshire, but also from Waddington in Lincolnshire and perhaps occasionally Waddington in Coulsdon (Surrey). The first two placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wada</i> + Old English connective <i>-ing-</i> + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Surrey placename derives from Old English <i>hwǣte</i> ‘wheat’, later <i>hwǣten</i> ‘growing with wheat’ + <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."]}]},{"name":"Judith","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, meaning ‘Jewess’ or ‘woman from Judea’, borne by a Jewish heroine whose story is recorded in the Book of Judith in the Apocrypha. Judith is portrayed as a beautiful widow who delivers her people from the invading Assyrians by gaining the confidence of their commander, Holofernes, and cutting off his head while he is asleep; without their commander, the Assyrians are duly routed. This has been a perennially popular Jewish name. In the English-speaking world it was taken up in the 16th century, having been in occasional use among Gentiles before this: for example, it was borne by a niece of William the Conqueror. It enjoyed great popularity between the 1940s and the 1960s. Today's notable bearers include the American novelist  Judith Krantz  (  b. 1928 ) and the Scottish composer  Judith Weir  (  b. 1954 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Judith Isabel Badlington was born in 1387, in Thame, Oxfordshire, England, her father, Robert Badlington, was 30 and her mother, Polly Babcock, was 27. She married Geoffrey Dormer III in 1408, in Buckinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1430, in Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1387–1430":"1387–1430","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1409–1470":"1409–1470","1417–1503":"1417–1503","1357–1430":"1357–1430","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1503":"1503","1357":"1357","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1417":"1417","Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"Thame, Oxfordshire, England","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1387–1430":"1387–1430","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1409–1470":"1409–1470","1417–1503":"1417–1503","1357–1430":"1357–1430","1360–1440":"1360–1440","1440":"1440","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","1503":"1503","1357":"1357","1389":"1389","1387":"1387","1430":"1430","1409":"1409","1408":"1408","1417":"1417","Thame, Oxfordshire, England":"Thame, Oxfordshire, England","Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, England":"Aylesbury, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England"},"fr":{"1387–1430":"1387–1430","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1409–1470":"1409–1470","141